<p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="7">Affordances </font></p><p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="5"><i>"term 
that refers to the properties of objects -- what sorts of operations and manipulations 
can be done to a particular object"</i> (D. A. Norman 1988, The Psychology 
of everyday things). </font></p><ul> <li><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="5">A 
door affords opening</font></li><li><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="5">A 
chair affords support</font></li></ul><p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="5">"perceived 
affordance": the extent to which objects suggest their affordance.</font></p><p><img src="affordances.jpg" alt="The image shows the affordances of door handles and scroll bars. The perceived performance of some elements is better than that of other elements." height="285" width="606"></p>
